comment:
I have an S24 Ultra and have had my Fold 7 since launch day. I honestly, and I mean honestly, expected to my S24 Ultra but every time I open up the Fold 7 display I can't help but think its the perfect device for me. 

I've had two Tab S8 Ultra; one broke soon after purchase while I sold the other after getting my Mac Mini. I mention my S8 Ultra because I thought I wanted a huge tablet to use on the go but ultimately THIS Z Fold 7 is the perfect tablet size for me. 

Somehow, somewy Samsung has pulled a magic trick with thermal dynamics of this phone. It. Never. Runs. Hot. No matter what I throw at it. 

My only critiques?

Wish the battery was better and while I intially critizied early reviewer for saying the lack of S-Pen support is a downgrade, unfortunately I do agree with them. 

The perfect Fold 8 FOR ME, would increase battery size/type, remove inner camera all together, put S-Pen back, start at 512 GB (my Fold 7 is 512 bc of preorder special) and perhaps make the outer display a tiny bit larger.

comment:
13:06 this doesn‚Äôt matter. The amount of ram is more for stability than it is for housing previously used applications in memory because there‚Äôs something really dumb Apple does that I see no one calling them out for. 

The way you expect apps to be held in ram ONLY applies to Apple‚Äôs own apps and NOT third party apps. 

Go ahead, launch phone, photos, pages, mail, messages etc but also load Reddit, bluesky, YouTube or whatever else you can think of. What happens to those third party apps?

They get thrown out of ram regardless of the fact that there‚Äôs plenty to store them. 

On the one hand, it makes iOS more efficient which I want more. On the other, people keep falsely praising the increase in ram when it doesn‚Äôt actually affect what folks think it does. I can‚Äôt tell you how many things I‚Äôve lost simply because I put my phone in my pocket either while the app was open or was the last app opened and I only went back to the homescreen before pocketing my phone. 

I have the iPhone 16 by the way and yeah, that 8gb of ram has been PHENOMENAL for the stability of my device but that‚Äôs it and while it‚Äôs greatly appreciated, I do feel I need to call it out when folks say the ram is doing things it doesn‚Äôt really do. 

Now, I haven‚Äôt tested this since iOS 26 released so maybe things are different but I doubt it. Also, no, the apps in question did not update in my pocket in case that would be a retort. They simply restart because that‚Äôs how iOS manages ram

14:04 this is the one thing I was desperate to find ANYBODY talk about and thank you for confirming it. A couple minutes is significant to me personally but if I‚Äôm watching peek brightness hdr in direct sunlight, I want to be able to watch the whole film without the screen dimming. Looks like that‚Äôs still not possible sadly even with the long awaited vapor chamber cooling

comment: I know people are complaining about the price but carriers and Samsung give great trade in deals. I had the Fold 4. If I traded that in for the S25 ultra, they would have only given me 400 for the phone, so I woud still pay around 899. However, my carrier (T-Mobile) gave 1100 for my Fold 4 if I went for the FOLD 7, so I would end up with the same price. I took the Fold7. Never used the pen so no loss there. Just wish the battery was better but I have a charger every where these days. Ive had it for a fews days an love it. Never going back to the old brick design. Should you pay 2000 for this for all its compromise, hell no. But nearly everyone I know is doing trade ins to get the price below 1000 which is what a lot of people spend on smart phones already. Hell, I have Apple people in my family who buy a new Apple phone each year which does hardly any sort innovation anymore (they used to when Jobs was still around). Thats insane.

comment:
I'm one of the few people it seems who minds neither the battery life or charging speed.
I get 24-26 hours of use on most days, granted it is not my main device. Work days it's in my pocket playing YouTube/music through Bluetooth sometimes and then using it during my breaks.
At home it's a small addition to my already existing tech.
And while it's an obvious solution: I charge while I sleep. Wireless, not even at full capacity. And yet it's always fully charged by the time I need it.

The inner camera is useful for video calls in flex mode, but going back to the under screen would be better in my eyes, slightly less clarity for an uninterrupted screen is worth it imo.

comment:
I'm trading my fold 5 for fold 7. I went to a retail store and see the difference myself, and man... the difference in just the weight, dimension, and feel just blew my mind. People may be asking, but is it worth the upgrade. For me, yes, because I heavily use my phone and I carry that phone in my pocket for over 10 hours at work standing and walking in a warehouse. The weight change is a huge plus for me. For me, the main upgrade is the weight and dimension. Bonus upgrade are better processor, camera, screen, the feel and hold. What I do on my fold: Heavy gaming, video watching, multi-tasking, music listening, window shopping. Basically, it's my walking PC.

For other people, it might not be worth the upgrade, especially if you are obsessed with the battery. If you are getting into the fold, fold 7 is definitely the way to go and a great start.

What I want in the future z fold? Micro SD slot, PLEASE! S Pen is always plus (for some reason, they decide to take out s pen on fold 7, smh*). Obviously, better battery life is always a plus. Less expensive price would be nice too.

comment:
Issues with this video

1) Durability
The iPhone 16 which you told to be strong durable is made up of the aluminum body similar to the iPhone 17 and iPhone 17 pro series. So, iPhone 17 pro should also have the same durability standards to your iPhone 16. But, scratches will be an issue on the 17 pro's plateau due to the sharp edges it has.¬†

2) Charging
You do not need to buy Apple's 40W charger to reach the claimed charging speeds, even with a non-AVS spec charger like Samsung's 45W charger, you can reach that same charging speeds. You can refer to GSMArena's 17 Pro Review, in its Charging Speed portion. It talks about this.

Apart from these, the other points stay valid and the iPhone 17 is plenty enough for 99% of the people.
